 mad Adam?'

'Because,' said Krug, 'I am the only person who can stand on the other end of the seesaw and make your end rise.'

Knuckles briskly rapped on the door and the zemberl marched in with a tinkling tray. He deftly served the two friends and presented a letter to Krug. Krug took a sip and read the note. 'Professor,' it said, 'this is still not the right manner. You should bear in mind that notwithstanding the narrow and fragile bridge of school memories uniting the two sides, these are s